[3] USA (District of Columbia)
Date: Mon 6 Nov 2017
Source: Washington Post [edited]
https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/11/06/mumps-reported-at-catholic-university-georgetown/


Mumps, an infectious disease carried on a sneeze or a cup, appears to be spreading among DC [USA, District of Columbia] universities, with cases reported at 3 schools.

The Catholic University of America recently identified a cluster of illness, with 4 confirmed mumps cases and 3 more suspected cases under investigation, a school spokeswoman said [Mon 6 Nov 2017].

On [Fri 3 Nov 2017], a message sent to the Georgetown University community said 2 undergraduates had been diagnosed with the disease.

The cases at Georgetown have been confirmed, according to a letter from the DC Department of Health.

And American University has 2 confirmed mumps cases, as well as 4 suspected cases, school spokesman Mark Story said [Mon 6 Nov 2017].

The mumps cases at DC universities appear to be connected, though officials are still investigating, DC Department of Health spokeswoman Jasmine Gossett said.

"We are monitoring them and are working with the universities and their student health centers, just to inform them and then educate those who may be at risk," Gossett said.

At Catholic, the school has adjusted Communion distribution during Mass to help combat the illness, university spokeswoman Elise Italiano said. "Normally, we offer Communion through the host and what we call the chalice, or the cup with wine," Italiano said. "And we suspended the 2nd practice . . . because of the possible spread through saliva. So, we've just taken that extra precaution."

Mumps spreads through saliva or mucus, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Symptoms include fever, headaches, and swollen and tender glands under the ears, the CDC's website notes.

Georgetown officials asked infected students to cloister themselves for 5 days after the appearance of initial symptoms, a note to the campus from Vince WinklerPrins, assistant vice president for student health, said.

"We will continue to monitor and support these students," WinklerPrins said.

In an email sent to its campus community, Catholic said residential students who had reported mumps symptoms have been moved to an unoccupied space, in an attempt to limit exposure.

"Students are able to return to rooms and classes after a 5-day period," the email stated.

Catholic's students were also briefed on how someone infected with mumps can spread the virus: by coughing or sharing a drink, for example. They were advised to keep their hands clean and to not share their utensils.

The University of Virginia [U-Va] has also recently urged students to take precautions after 2 suspected cases were identified. A U-Va spokesman did not immediately return an email seeking an update [Mon 6 Nov 2017].

[Byline: Sarah Larimer]

